iBumblebee is an auxiliary tool for NVidia graphics cards on the Linux		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iplatform. It enables NVidia cards to utilize Optimus technology,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iallowing laptops to render with dedicated graphics while displaying		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithrough integrated graphics—essentially hardware-accelerated graphics		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iswitching.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThis is an extremely useful tool, but it once suffered a severe bug		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(though three years ago) where a single space caused the deletion of		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe `/usr` directory for a large number of Ubuntu users.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIt happened during a Git update, with changes in `install.sh`:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iDue to a single space, the deletion command shifted from targeting		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`/usr/lib/nvidia-current/xorg/xorg` to deleting two separate		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idirectories: `/usr` and `/lib/nvidia-current/xorg/xorg`. The `/usr`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idirectory is where all your programs reside, including `apt-get`...		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
